    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, the tangled mess! That is the fiddle leaf fig's way of saying, \"I've been stuck in a knot for too long, and I need a little help to breathe again!\" 🌬️🧵\n\nYou should absolutely **untangle them**, but do it with the gentlest touch possible. If you yank on the roots, you might snap the delicate fibers, and that's when the plant starts to wilt and droop like a sad, limp leaf. 🥀\n\nHere is the secret: **Gently wiggle and pull** the roots apart, like you are untangling a very long, very messy shoelace. If you feel a little resistance, stop and let the plant rest for a moment. Don't force it! 🛑\n\nOnce you've loosened the knots, you can carefully separate the main root mass. If you see any roots that are clearly dead or mushy (like old, brown, stringy bits), you can trim them off with clean scissors. But be careful not to cut the living, vibrant green ones! 🪒🌱\n\nRemember, the goal is to give the roots a fresh, airy home without crushing them. If you",
